{
  "texts": [
    "Thus D KL (p∥q) = - A p(x) log(1 + ζ(x)) dx - B p(x) log(1 + ζ(x)) dx ≥ -α A p(x)ζ(x) dx - B p(x)ζ(x) dx + β B p(x)ζ(x) 2 dx = (1 -α) A p(x)ζ(x) dx + β Ω p(x)ζ(x) 2 dx = (1 -log 2) A |q(x) -p(x)| dx + B p(x) q(x) -p(x) p(x) 2 dx.For the first term in right hand side of the above equality, we haveA |q(x)-p(x)| dx ≥ 1 2τ A |q(x) -p(x)| 2 dx.For the second term, we have B p(x) q(x)-p(x) p(x)2 dx ≥ 1 2τ B |q(x) -p(x)| 2 dx.",
    "Finally, we have D KL (p∥q) ≥ 1-log 2 2τ Ω |q(x) -p(x)| 2 dx.Proof of Theorem 3.2.",
    "The proof is inspired by the methodologies used in [4, Proposition 1] and [33,Appendix E].",
    "However, dealing with the Lévy term introduces substantial complexity, requiring the introduction of novel techniques for a thorough analysis.This manuscript is for review purposes only.Firstly, according to the definition of KL divergence, we derive thatd dt D KL (p θ t ∥ pt) = d dt Ω log p θ t (x) pt(x) p θ t (x) dx = - Ω p θ t (x) pt(x) ∂t pt(x) dx + Ω log p θ t (x) pt(x) ∂tp θ t (x) dx + Ω ∂tp θ t (x) dx = - Ω p θ t (x) pt(x) ∂t pt(x) dx + Ω log p θ t (x) pt(x) ∂tp θ t (x) dx = - Ω V[ pt](x, t) • ∇ p θ t (x) pt(x) pt(x) dx + Ω f θ (x, t) • ∇ log p θ t (x) pt(x) p θ t (x) dx = - Ω V[ pt](x, t) -f θ (x, t) + V[p θ t](x, t) -V[p θ t](x, t) • ∇ log p θ t (x) pt(x) p θ t (x) dx,where we used ∂ t p θ t (x) dx = 0 and the integration by parts.",
    "With the expression V[p θ t] of (3.1), we decompose the derivative of the KL divergence as follows,d dt D KL (p θ t ∥ pt) = Ω f θ (x, t) -V[p θ t](x, t) • ∇ log p θ t (x) pt(x) p θ t (x) dx Perturbation + Ω Ω K(x -y)(p θ t (y) -pt(y)) dy • ∇ log p θ t (x) pt(x) p θ t (x) dx Interaction - Ω 1 2 ∇ log p θ t (x) pt(x) 2 Σ(x,t) p θ t (x) dx Diffusion + Ω It(p θ t, F, G)(x) -It( pt, F, G)(x) • ∇ log p θ t (x) pt(x) p θ t (x) dx Lévy, where | • | 2 Σ(x,t) = ⟨•, Σ(x, t)•⟩.The bounds for these four terms are studied below respectively in four steps."
